<TR BACKGROUND="" BGCOLOR="#000000"><TD COLSPAN=3><TABLE WIDTH=100% CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR><TD WIDTH=200 ALIGN="LEFT">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href="/cgi-bin/advent.pl?day=2&show_all=1"><font size=2>&lt;&lt;&lt;&nbsp;DEC&nbsp;2</font></a></TD><TD WIDTH=200 ALIGN="CENTER"><a href="/cgi-bin/advent.pl"><font size=2>HOME</font></a></TD><TD ALIGN="CENTER"><a class="addthis_button" href="http://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=250&amp;pub=xa-4b157e7f1b908808"><img src="http://s7.addthis.com/static/btn/v2/lg-share-en.gif" width="125" height="16" alt="Bookmark and Share" style="border:0"/></a><script type="text/javascript" src="http://s7.addthis.com/js/250/addthis_widget.js#pub=xa-4b157e7f1b908808"></script></TD><TD WIDTH=200 ALIGN="RIGHT"><a href="/cgi-bin/advent.pl?day=4&show_all=1"><font size=2>DEC&nbsp;4&nbsp;&gt;&gt;&gt;</font></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD></TR></TABLE></TD></TR>
<TR HEIGHT=5><TD COLSPAN=3 BACKGROUND="" BGCOLOR="#000000"></TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=5 BACKGROUND="" BGCOLOR="#000000"></TD>
<TD BACKGROUND="/black6.png">
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5><TR><TD>
	<TABLE WIDTH=100% CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR><TD>
<IMG ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=130 HEIGHT=130 SRC="chocs/choc_day_3.png" ALT="chocolate"><IMG ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=190 SRC="globes/advent_globe_3.png" ALT="snowglobe"><table cellpadding=10 align="center" background="/black4.png" width=430><TR><TD><center><font size=6 color="#ffff00"><b><i>GAUNTLET</i></b></font><br><font size=3 color="red"><b><i>22 days to Christmas</i></b></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><p>
1986 was the tipping point in terms of pre-Christmas magazine hype.
Rarely would a game get a double-page preview spread unless it was
utterly remarkable. Even major Christmas releases weren't guaranteed
coverage beyond a full page, and magazines were still learning just
what makes a great page design for inspiring excitement for an
upcoming title. You were lucky to get more than a few paragraphs of
text plus a scattering of screenshots.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<TABLE ALIGN="left" WIDTH=300 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD><a href="pngs/d3_1986_pre3.png" target="1986_pre3.png"><IMG SRC="pngs/d3_1986_pre3_small.jpg" WIDTH=300 HEIGHT=213></a></TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSPAN=1 ALIGN="CENTER"><font size=-1 color="yellow"><b><i>C&VG was the first magazine to really take on double-page spreads for previews</i></b></font></TD></TR>
</TABLE><TABLE ALIGN="right" WIDTH=150 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD><a href="pngs/d3_1986_pre4.png" target="1986_pre4.png"><IMG SRC="pngs/d3_1986_pre4_small.jpg" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=215></a></TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSPAN=1 ALIGN="CENTER"><font size=-1 color="yellow"><b><i>You get the feeling here that YS wanted to push the envelope and felt restricted by single-page features.</i></b></font></TD></TR>
</TABLE>So perhaps it's not so surprising that one of the most fondly
remembered Spectrum games and US Gold's major title for Christmas 1986
only merited little more than a few paragraphs and pics. Slowly
magazines were catching on that hype was visual as well as literal,
and it would take until 1987 for the pre-Christmas hype cycle to fully
kick in, artwork-covered double-page spreads and all.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The <i>Gauntlet</i> arcade game was huge - both physically and socially. The
four-player arcade machine had to be large enough for everyone to
stand around, meaning the screen also had to be large, or at least
seemed like it at the time. When you're twelve, everything seems
larger when it feels like a novelty.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;It was one of the first games which I noticed could be extended for as
long as you pumped coins into the machine until everyone's pockets
<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN="left"><TR><TD><TABLE WIDTH=222 ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" BGCOLOR="#000000" BACKGROUND=""><TR><TD><center><object width="212" height="172"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/7mMJio2MO6w&hl=en_GB&fs=1&"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/7mMJio2MO6w&hl=en_GB&fs=1&" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="212" height="172"></embed></object><br>
<FONT size=-1 COLOR="#FFFF00"><b><u>Gauntlet Original Arcade Footage</u></b></font></center><font size=-1 color="#ffffff">Over twenty years on and I still love the sampled speech... <b><i>(4:31)</i></b></font><center><font size=-2 color="#ffffff"><i>Watch full-sized <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7mMJio2MO6w" target="7mMJio2MO6w">at YouTube</a></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><br></TD></TR></TABLE>

were empty. The basic dungeons and dragons motif felt fresh and new,
as well as playing with your friends who could help and hinder you if
they felt like it.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<TABLE ALIGN="right" WIDTH=150 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD><a href="pngs/d3_gauntlet_arcade.png" target="gauntlet_arcade.png"><IMG SRC="pngs/d3_gauntlet_arcade_small.jpg" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=195></a></TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSPAN=1 ALIGN="CENTER"><font size=-1 color="yellow"><b><i>Four joysticks, four coinslots, eight fire buttons, pure joy when you have a foursome. But no one wanted to be Thyra.</i></b></font></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
But the arcade version also had a hook. One single, glorious, hook.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<b><i>"ELF IS ABOUT TO DIE"</i></b>
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Sampled speech and sound effects combined to give the perfect atmosphere.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The Spectrum version inevitably felt a little diluted as a result. The
four-player game became a two-player game, the sound practically
disappeared, but the playability shone through. Even though rival
software houses beat US Gold to the punch with their clones of the
game, it was the official conversion of <i>Gauntlet</i> which everybody
remembers, and remembers fondly - fondly enough for US Gold to produce
extra levels for it in 1987 and to then release two further sequels.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD></TR><TR><TD><IMG SRC="chocs/voxpop.png" ALIGN="LEFT"><br><TABLE BACKGROUND="/black7.png"><TR><TD><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR="#ffff00"><B><I>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;BRIAN GAFF&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</I></B></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><br>
<b>Brian Gaff ran a few support services for the Spectrum and SAM Coupe back in the day, and was the British agent for Gerton Lunter's ground-breaking Z80 Spectrum emulator - I remember begging him for the latest version of Z80 just so I'd be able to play <i>North And South</i> over one Christmas break. Brian also answered letters on Micronet as his alter-ego Warthog, so you have two replies for the price of one! Brian's are in green, Warthog's in purple.</b><br><br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Who are you and what are you up to?<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN="left"><TR><TD><TABLE WIDTH=222 ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" BGCOLOR="#000000" BACKGROUND=""><TR><TD><center><object width="212" height="172"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/cyRqR56aCKc&hl=en_GB&fs=1&"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/cyRqR56aCKc&hl=en_GB&fs=1&" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="212" height="172"></embed></object><br>
<FONT size=-1 COLOR="#FFFF00"><b><u>Ghostbusters Trailer</u></b></font></center><font size=-1 color="#ffffff">One of those films you <i>have</i> to watch. As there was no local cinema where I grew up, seeing it in the Christmas TV Times made me overjoyed. <b><i>(2:13)</i></b></font><center><font size=-2 color="#ffffff"><i>Watch full-sized <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cyRqR56aCKc" target="cyRqR56aCKc">at YouTube</a></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><br></TD></TR></TABLE>
</font></i></b><br>
<font color="#50ff50">I'm Brian Gaff,  claim to dubious fame.. Was involved in the Spectrum area of Micronet, was a supporter and  helper for the Sam. Did some bits for Pop Com Weekly. Still owed money by  Robert Maxwell.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;For those who saw my Micronet  letters replies...</font>
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<font color="#b060f0">Warthog: Actually, Brian is completely mad and is currently engaged in fighting the Government over disability benefit cuts.</font>
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Favourite cracker gift (aside from fortune-telling fish, naturally)?</font></i></b><br>
<font color="#50ff50">I like quiet crackers since losing my sight. Its very disconcerting when you do not know somone near you is pulling one.. Gift? Well, I found a fridge magnet in one once, no wonder it was heavy. But the Santa apparently looked chinese.</font>
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<font color="#b060f0">Warthog:The only cracker Brian wants to pull  is female and has lots of tactile areas to feel.</font>
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Favourite Christmas Song</font></i></b><br>
<font color="#50ff50">Oh, Bob Rivers  send up of the Bruce Springstein one, its called Santa Clause is foolin around.</font>
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<font color="#b060f0">Warthog: Brian does not do christmas these days, so Silent Night should be his favourite!</font>
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Best Speccy Christmas memory?<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN="right"><TR><TD><TABLE WIDTH=222 ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" BGCOLOR="#000000" BACKGROUND=""><TR><TD><center><object width="212" height="172"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/UpKcU1thiLw&hl=en_GB&fs=1&"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/UpKcU1thiLw&hl=en_GB&fs=1&" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="212" height="172"></embed></object><br>
<FONT size=-1 COLOR="#FFFF00"><b><u>Christmas 1984 adverts</u></b></font></center><font size=-1 color="#ffffff">Featuring a rather non-festive Coke ad, plus bonus Weetabix gang. <b><i>(3:47)</i></b></font><center><font size=-2 color="#ffffff"><i>Watch full-sized <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UpKcU1thiLw" target="UpKcU1thiLw">at YouTube</a></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><br></TD></TR></TABLE>
</font></i></b><br>
<font color="#50ff50">Well, many of them going to the Microfairs just before it. I bought many gadgets then, programmable joysticks, drive interfaces, silly software for hacking into programs. I miss that as I now gather its a major offence on the PC.</font>
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Favourite Quality Street chocolate?</font></i></b><br>
<font color="#50ff50">You will love this one. I don't eat them. Most chocolate gives me a headache. As someone said, all the more for us then!</font>
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<font color="#b060f0">Warthog: Headache? He does not eat them as he is scared of dentists..</font>
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Best present ever?</font></i></b><br>
<font color="#50ff50">Well, not Speccy related, but it was when I was very young. it was called Radionics and was for those who liked electronics, the equivelent of mechano. Many nice bits of gadgetry made, not entirely as per the documentation and all with no solder.</font>
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<font color="#b060f0">Warthog: You should see some of the birds nest he made when he could use solder though, one of them is still operating the porch light. Expecting an explosion any day...</font>
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Speccy game you most looked forward to?</font></i></b><br>
<font color="#50ff50">Well, I looked forward to <i>Elite</i>, but found it a bit too hard and far too easy to cheat of course. First job was to bypass lenslok of course.
The best game of all was a cheap one called <i>Combat Zone</i>.</font>
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<font color="#b060f0">Warthog: He also played that darned <i>Silkworm</i> till we all got sick of those flashes and noises too.</font>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE><p>
